'''''Map of China''''' is a 2008 [[sculpture]] by [[Chinese people|Chinese]] artist [[Ai Weiwei]].<ref name="The Daily Telegraph - 12Oct2010 - Ai Weiwei's 'Map of China': setting a new benchmark">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/art/art-features/8050796/Ai-Weiweis-Map-of-China-setting-a-new-benchmark.html|title=Ai Weiwei's 'Map of China': setting a new benchmark|last=Secher|first=Benjamin|date=12 October 2010|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>  The sculpture has been reported as resembling a [[Bench (furniture)#Different types of benches|park bench]] or tree trunk,<ref name="The Korea Times - 09May2008 - Artist Ai Weiwei Holds First Exhibit">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2009/05/148_23953.html|title=Artist Ai Weiwei Holds First Exhibit |last=Garcia|first=Cathy Rose A. |date=9 May 2008|work=[[The Korea Times]]|accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref> but its cross-section is a map of [[China]].  It is four [[metre]]s long and weighs 635 [[kilogram]]s.<ref name="The Daily Telegraph - 12Oct2010 - Ai Weiwei's 'Map of China': setting a new benchmark"/> It is made from wood salvaged from [[Qing Dynasty]] temples.<ref name="The Korea Times - 09May2008 - Artist Ai Weiwei Holds First Exhibit"/><ref name="The New Republic - 01Feb2013 - Ai Weiwei: Wonderful dissident, terrible artist ">{{cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/112218/ai-wei-wei-wonderful-dissident-terrible-artist|title=Ai Weiwei: Wonderful dissident, terrible artist |last=Perl|first=Jed|date=1 February 2013|work=[[The New Republic]]|publisher=[[Chris Hughes]]|accessdate=2 April 2013}}</ref>

