'''Mary Kathryn "Polly" Anthony''' (1958–2013) was an American music industry executive. One of the first women to head a major record label, she was the president of [[Epic Records]] from 1997 until 2003.<ref name="Rolling Stone obit" /><ref name="book">{{cite book|last1=O'Brien|first1=Lucy|title=She Bop II: The Definitive History of Women in Rock, Pop and Soul|date=April 1, 2004|publisher=Bayou Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0826472083|pages=548|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V1mtAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA435&dq=She+Bop+Polly+Anthony&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiKjaW62ofVAhUHS2MKHWTeAhsQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=She%20Bop%20Polly%20Anthony&f=false|accessdate=14 July 2017}}</ref><ref name="Variety obit">{{cite news|last1=Variety staff|title=Polly Anthony, Former Epic Records Chief, Dies at 59|url=https://variety.com/2013/music/obituaries-people-news/polly-anthony-former-epic-records-chief-dies-at-59-1200689505/|accessdate=14 July 2017|work=Variety/AP|date=October 2, 2013}}</ref>
==Early life== Anthony was born in Alexandria, Virginia to Patrice H. and Bernard J. Anthony, an aerospace executive. She and her family moved to Palos Verdes Peninsula in Southern California in 1963. In 1965, she saw [[The Beatles]] at the [[Hollywood Bowl]], a concert which "pointed the way to the road her life would take."<ref name="Daily Breeze obit">{{cite news|title=Mary Anthony Obituary|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/dailybreeze/obituary.aspx?pid=168227598|accessdate=14 July 2017|work=Daily Breeze|date=November 29, 2013}}</ref><ref name="HR obit" />
==Career== Anthony began her career in the music industry at RCA Records. She worked briefly at an artist management company and in 1978 was hired as an assistant to the head of promotion at Epic Associated Labels. She "assiduously worked her way up the ladder," and in 1988 moved to New York to become the senior vice president of promotion at Epic. In 1993 Anthony became the president of [[550 Music]], an Epic imprint, and in 1997 she was appointed president of Epic Records. Over the course of her career at Epic, she worked with artists including [[Celine Dion]], [[Michael Jackson]], [[Pearl Jam]], and [[Rage Against the Machine]].<ref name="HR obit" /><ref name="billboard pres epic">{{cite news|last1=Newman|first1=Melinda|title=Anthony Adds Epic Stripes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AwoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA7&dq=polly+anthony+epic&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj93OzexYfVAhXosFQKHS2tAEwQ6AEIRjAG#v=onepage&q=polly%20anthony%20epic&f=false|accessdate=14 July 2017|work=Billboard|date=September 27, 1997}}</ref>
In 2003 Anthony returned to California as the president of [[Dreamworks Records]]; after a corporate reorganization, she was named co-president of [[Geffen Records]].<ref name="LA Times Geffen">{{cite news|last1=Leeds|first1=Jeff|title=Geffen Label is Expected to Name Co-President|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/mar/06/business/fi-interscope6|accessdate=14 July 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 6, 2004}}</ref> In 2006, she became head of television and film for the [[Universal Music Group]]. She left Universal in 2010 to executive produce film and television projects. Among others, Anthony produced the HBO series ''Off the Record'', ''Cane'' for CBS, and ''Betty & Coretta'' for Lifetime.<ref name="HR obit">{{cite news|last1=Christman|first1=Ed|title=Music Industry Veteran Polly Anthony Dies at 59|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/music-industry-veteran-polly-anthony-638892|accessdate=14 July 2017|date=September 29, 2013}}</ref>
Anthony died of pancreatic cancer in September 2013.<ref name="Rolling Stone obit">{{cite news|last1=Knopper|first1=Steve|title=Polly Anthony, Former Epic Records President, Dead at 60|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/polly-anthony-former-epic-records-president-dead-at-59-20131001|accessdate=14 July 2017|work=Rolling Stone|date=October 1, 2013}}</ref>
